   <h2>-:Diffierence between Body Selector and Universal(*)Selector:-</h2>
   <div><ol><li>Body Selector:-</li>
        <p>if we add an background-image by element selector,background image will be displayed to the whole Wedpage this is called body selector.</p>
        <li>Universal(*) Selector:-</li>
         <p>if we add an background-image by element selector,background image will be displayed accoding to the inline and block level element this is called Universal Selector.</p>
</ol></div></details><hr>
<details><summary>Task-2 on 27/11/2023</summary>
    <h2>Documentation of CSS Selectors:-</h2>
<div><ol><li>Element selector:</li>
    <p>In CSS, an element selector targets and styles HTML elements based on their tag names.</p>
<pre><strong>
    syntax:-   h1{
        color:rgb(0,20,28)
    } 
</strong></pre>
<li>Universal selector:</li>
<p>In CSS, the universal selector(*)selects and style all elements on a webpage.</p>
<pre><strong>
    syntax:-    *{
        background-color:green
    }

</strong></pre>
<li>Group selects:</li>
<p>In CSS, a group selector combines multple selectors to apply the same style rules to multiple elements.</p>
<pre><strong>
    syntax:-   h1,p,div{
        text-align:center;
        text-decoration-line:underline;
        color:red;
    }

</strong></pre>
<li>ID selector:</li>
<p>In CSS,an Id selector style a specific HTML element(Uniqeu #)with a Uniqeu identifier assigned using the "id" attribute.</p>
<pre><strong>
    syntax:-
    #link{
           text-shadow:3px 0px 2px green
         }

</strong></pre>
<li>Class selector:</li>
<p>In CSS ,a class selector targets and styles HTML elements with a specified class(.) attribute.</p>
<pre><strong>
    syntax:-
    .demo{
       text-align:right;
       color:blue;
    }

</strong></pre>
<li>Element.class selector:</li>
<p>In CSS, an Element.class selector is a give a particular class selector to the Element selector.</p>
</ol>
<pre><strong>
   syntax:-    h3.class{
                  color:yellow;
                  line-height:2;
                  text-indent:20px;
                }
</strong></pre></div></details><hr>
<details id="hello"><summary>Task-1 on 28/11/2023</summary>
<h2>&#9733 Commbinator Selectors in CSS &#9733</h2>
<p>Commbinator Selector:<br>
    A combinator is something that explains the relationship between the selectors. A CSS selector can contain more than one simple selector. Between the simple selectors, we can include a combinator. </p>
<ol><div>
<li>Descendent selector:</li>
<p>In CSS,a descendent selector selects an element that is a descendent of another specified element.</p>
<pre><strong>
   syntax:-   div p{
                 background-color:orange;
                 color:blue;
            }

</strong></pre>
<li>Child selector:</li>
<p>In CSS,a child selector targets and styles elements that are direct children of a specified parent element.</p>
<pre><strong>
syntax:-   div>h1{
     text-transforms:capitalize;
     text-decoration-style:wavy;
    }
</strong></pre>
<li>Adjacent Sibling Selector:</li>
<p>The adjacent sibling selector is used to select an element that is directly after another specific element. Sibling elements must have the same parent element, and "adjacent" means "immediately following"
    is called 'Adjacent sibling selector'.</p>
<pre><strong>
 Syntax:-   div+ul{
    background-color:black;
    color:red;
 }   
</strong></pre>

<li>General Sibling Selector:</li></ol></div>
<p>The General Selector is specified by a tilde sign (~) in CSS and is a selector that helps in selecting the sibling elements of the same parent without them even being adjacent to each other.

    In other words, unlike the Adjacent Sibling selector which selects only the elements that immediately follow a specific element, the General Sibling Selector selects the element that shares the same parent element regardless of them being adjacent or not. </p>
<pre><strong>
    Syntax:-  div~p{
        color:brown;
        background-color:light green;
    }
</strong></pre>
</details>
